{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e72be14c-0131-4f33-b556-09e1ea7883fc","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit embeds the skip reason in the test attribute itself (`Fact`/`Theory`), while the others use a separate attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07adb836-2d2e-4f12-81c1-44b00d91237e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":310,"requestId":"9825:19EA9:1BCCBE:243575:69FFDC52"},"id":"70cfc66c-17a8-4593-80c4-2f5db7da9aca","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:16:10.350Z","parentId":"5a9e45ee-600f-4d71-8596-fe41de22c519"}
